f-2010 \"42nd Box-Office Entertainment Awards honors outstanding actors and actresses of 2010\"]. ''Pep.ph''. Retrieved 2014-05-21.</ref>\n* [[2012 GMMSF Box-Office Entertainment Awards|2012 Winner]], Most Popular TV Program News & Public Affairs<ref>[http://www.pep.ph/news/33760/this-week-in-photo-news/1/1#focus \"Vice Ganda named Phenomenal Box-Office Star; Derek Ramsay is Box-Office King while Anne Curtis and Cristine Reyes share Box-Office Queen title\"]. ''Pep.ph''. Retrieved 2014-05-20.</ref>\n* [[2013 GMMSF Box-Office Entertainment Awards|2013 Winner]], Most Popular TV Program News & Public Affairs<ref>[http://www.pep.ph/photos/3796/44th-guillermo-mendoza-box-office-entertainment-awards \"44th Guillermo Mendoza Box-Office Entertainment Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403190603/http://www.pep.ph/photos/3796/44th-guillermo-mendoza-box-office-entertainment-awards |date=April 3, 2019 }}. ''Pep.ph''. Retrieved 2014-05-19.</ref>\n\n:'''Northwest Samar State University Annual Awards'''\n* 2013 Winner, Best News and Public Affairs Program\n* 2013 Winner, Mike Enriquez: Best News and Public Affairs Male Program Anchor\n* 2013 Winner, Mel Tiangco: Best News and Public Affairs Female Program Anchor\n* 2012 Winner, Best News and Public Affairs Program\n* 2012 Winner, Mike Enriquez: Best News and Public Affairs Male Program Anchor\n\n:'''PMAP Makatao Awards for Media Excellence'''\n* 2012 Winner, Best News Program\n* 2012 Winner, Mel Tiangco: Best TV Female Newscaster\n\n:'''National Academy of Television Arts & Science (Emmy Awards)'''\n* 2013 Winner, Best Documentary\n\n==''24 Oras Weekend''==\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = 24 Oras Weekend\n| image = 24 Oras Weekend title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card since 2019\n| genre = [[Newscast]]\n| company = [[GMA News and Public Affairs]]\n| director = Lirio Dayao\n| presenter = {{plain list|\n* [[Pia Arcangel]]\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]]}}\n| theme_music_composer = Jimmy Antiporda\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| executive_producer = Nielsen Ocampo\n| location = {{plainlist|\n* Studio 2, [[GMA Network Center]], [[Quezon City]], Philippines {{small|(2010\u20132011, 2018\u20132019)}}\n* Studio 5, GMA Network Center, Quezon City, Philippines {{small|(2011\u20132018, since 2019)}}}}\n| runtime = 30-45 minutes\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| picture_format = {{plainlist|\n* [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n* [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])}}\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|2010|2|21}}\n| last_aired = present\n}}\n\nOriginally anchored by [[Pia Arcangel]] and [[Jiggy Manicad]], the weekend edition of ''24 Oras'' premiered on February 21, 2010 on the network's Saturday and Sunday night line up replacing ''[[GMA Weekend Report]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=24 Oras Weekend premieres this Sunday, February 21 |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/5612/24-oras-weekend-premieres-this-sunday-february-21 |accessdate=April 26, 2018 |work=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]] |date=February 20, 2012}}</ref> On April 21, 2018, Manicad left the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2018/04/22/1808377/jiggy-manicad-leaves-media-next-level-public-service |title=Jiggy Manicad leaves media for \u2018next level\u2019 of public service {{!}} Philstar.com |website=philstar.com |accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, [[Ivan Mayrina]] became an anchor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/43076/ivan-mayrina-co-anchors-24-oras-weekend/story |title=Ivan Mayrina co-anchors '24 Oras Weekend' |website=www.gmanetwork.com |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Arcangel and Mayrina currently serve as anchors.\n\n===Anchors===\n* [[Pia Arcangel]] {{small|(since 2010)}}\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]] {{small|(since 2018)}}\n* Nelson Canlas {{small|(since 2013, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n\n;Former anchors\n* [[Jiggy Manicad]] {{small|(2010\u20132018)}}\n* [[Grace Lee]] {{small|(2010\u20132012, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n* [[Luane Dy]] {{small|(2010\u20132013, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n* Cata Tibayan {{small|(2013\u20132018, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n\n===Ratings===\nAccording to [[AGB Nielsen Philippines]]' Mega Manila household television ratings, the premiere of ''24 Oras Weekend'' earned a 18.4% rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/news/local/24798/agb-mega-manila-tv-ratings-feb-19-22-panday-kids-and-pilipinas-got-talent-make-strong-impact-on-thei |title=AGB Mega Manila TV Ratings (Feb. 19-22): Panday Kids and Pilipinas Got Talent make strong impact on their debut |author=Santiago, Erwin |date=February 23, 2010 |accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Regional versions==\n*  ''24 Oras Amianan''\n* ''[[24 Oras Bikol]]''\n* ''24 Oras Central Visayas''\n* ''24 Oras Davao''\n* ''[[24 Oras Ilokano]]''\n* ''24 Oras North Central Luzon''\n* ''[[24 Oras Northern Mindanao]]''\n* ''24 Oras Southern Mindanao''\n* ''24 Oras Western Visayas''\n* ''[[Ratsada 24 Oras]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/shows/24oras}}\n* {{IMDb title|0764672}}\n\n{{24 Oras}}\n{{PhilNetworkEveningNewsShows}}\n{{PhilNetworkHourlyNewsBulletins}}\n{{GMA Network (current and upcoming original programming)}}\n{{GMA News and Public Affairs}}\n\n[[Category:GMA Network news programs]]\n[[Category:GMA News and Public Affairs programs]]\n[[Category:Philippine television news programs]]\n[[Category:2004 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s Philippine television series]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Flagship evening news programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|24 Horas}}\n{{short description|Philippine television show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = 24 Oras\n| image = 24 Oras title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card since 2019\n| genre = [[Newscast]]\n| company = [[GMA News and Public Affairs]]\n| director = Joel San Luis\n| presenter = {{plain list|\n* [[Mel Tiangco]]\n* [[Mike Enriquez]]\n* [[Vicky Morales]]}}\n| narrated = {{plainlist|\n* Joel Reyes Zobel {{small|(2004\u20132014)}}\n* Mike Enriquez {{small|(since 2014)}}}}\n| theme_music_composer = Jimmy Antiporda\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| executive_producer = Antonio Magsumbol \n| location = {{plainlist|\n* Studio 2, [[GMA Network Center]], [[Quezon City]], Philippines {{small|(2004\u20132011, 2018\u20132019)}}\n* Studio 5, GMA Network Center, Quezon City, Philippines {{small|(2011\u20132018, since 2019)}}}}\n| runtime = 75-90 minutes\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| picture_format = {{plainlist|\n* [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n* [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])}}\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|2004|3|15}}\n| last_aired = present\n| website = http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/shows/24oras\n}}\n\n'''''24 Oras''''' (pronounced as Bente Kwatro Oras / {{translation|24 Hours}}) is a [[Philippine television]] newscast show broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. Originally anchored by [[Mel Tiangco]] and [[Mike Enriquez]], it premiered on March 15, 2004 replacing ''[[Frontpage: Ulat ni Mel Tiangco]]'' on the network's Telebabad line up and worldwide on [[GMA Pinoy TV]]. Tiangco, Enriquez and [[Vicky Morales]] currently serve as anchors.\n\nThe show is simultaneously broadcasting on radio through [[DZBB-AM|Super Radyo DZBB 594]] and its [[List of GMA Network radio stations#Super Radyo AM stations|regional stations]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:P 20161121 160036 p.jpg|left|thumb|358x358px|A billboard for the show in [[GMA Network Center]]]]\n''24 Oras'' premiered on March 15, 2004 and it was first broadcast from the Studio 2 of [[GMA Network Center]], replacing ''[[Frontpage: Ulat ni Mel Tiangco]]''. [[Mel Tiangco]] and [[Mike Enriquez]] served as anchors, while [[Pia Guanio]] served as the anchor for ''Showbiz Time''.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eFONogODqGg 24 Oras pilot episode (camrecorded)</ref>\n\nOn February 21, 2011, the show moved to Studio 5 of [[GMA Network Center]]. On June 4, 2012, the segment ''I.M. Ready: GMA Weather'' was launched featuring Nathaniel Cruz. On November 10, 2014, [[Vicky Morales]] was hired an anchor.<ref name=\"Vicki\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/387200/cbb/gma-news-and-public-affairs-announces-big-changes-in-news-lineup/ |title=GMA News and Public Affairs announces big changes in news lineup |website=GMA News Online}}</ref> In May 2015, [[Pia Guanio]] left the show.<ref name=\"Pia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/495002/full-statement-gma-network-on-pia-guanio-s-departure-from-24-oras/story/ |title=FULL STATEMENT: GMA Network on Pia Guanio\u2019s departure from 24 Oras |work=GMA News Online |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Iya Villania]] was hired as the new ''Chika Minute'' anchor on June 15, 2015.<ref name=\"Iya\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/502314/iya-villania-is-new-24-oras-chika-minute-host/story/ |title=Iya Villania is new 24 Oras \u2018Chika Minute\u2019 host |work=GMA News Online |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> On August 24, 2018, [[Atom Araullo]] served as a substitute anchor for Enriquez, who went on medical leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://showbizchika.net/atom-araullo-temporarily-replaces-mike-enriquez-in-24-oras/v|title=Atom Araullo temporarily replaces Mike Enriquez in 24 Oras|work=ShowBiz Chika |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |language=en-us}}</ref> Enriquez returned on November 26, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/46079/look-mike-enriquez-returns-to-24-oras/story |title=LOOK: Mike Enriquez returns to 24 Oras |author=Soriano, Gia Allana |website=www.gmanetwork.com |accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Anchors==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|image1 = Mike Enriquez in White Plains, Quezon City.jpg\n|caption1 = Mike Enriquez serves as an anchor.\n|width1 = 150\n}}\n\n* [[Mel Tiangco]] {{small|(since 2004)}}\n* [[Mike Enriquez]] {{small|(since 2004)}}\n* [[Vicky Morales]] {{small|(since 2014)}}<ref name=\"Vicki\"/>\n* Nathaniel \"Mang Tani\" Cruz {{small|(since 2012, ''I.M. Ready: GMA Weather'')}}\n* [[Iya Villania]] {{small|(since 2015, ''Chika Minute'')}}<ref name=\"Iya\"/>\n* [[Atom Araullo]] {{small|(2004\u20132005; ''Atomic Sports'', since 2018; interim anchor)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-ph/entertainment/celebrity/netizens-express-delight-with-gma-network-newscasters-wearing-abs-cbns-theme-colors/ar-BBZXXhW |title=Netizens express delight with GMA Network newscasters wearing ABS-CBN\u2019s theme colors |author=De Leon, Angelle De Leon |date=February 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Jessica Soho]] {{small|(since 2020; interim anchor)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/61054/24-oras-jessica-soho-and-vicky-morales-praised-by-netizens-in-handling-koko-pimentel-interview/story |title='24 Oras,' Jessica Soho, and Vicky Morales praised by netizens in handling Koko Pimentel interview |author=Garcia, Cara Emmeline |date=March 26, 2020 |accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Former anchors\n* [[Pia Guanio]] {{small|(2004\u20132015; ''Chika Minute'')}}<ref name=\"Pia\"/>\n\n==Segments==\n* ''Chika Minute''\n* ''Good News''\n* ''I.M. Ready, GMA Weather''\n* ''Kapusong Totoo''\n* ''Pampa Good Vibes''\n* ''Patok of the Town''\n* ''Sumbungan ng Bayan''\n* ''#SummerVibes''\n* ''Time Out''\n* ''Usapang Pets''\n* ''Viral na 'To!''\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Awards\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2004\n| Catholic Mass Media Awards\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Best News Program\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''24 Oras''\n| {{won}}\n! rowspan=\"4\" |\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[18th PMPC Star Awards for Television]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Female Newscaster\n| [[Mel Tiangco]]\