nne Curtis and Cristine Reyes share Box-Office Queen title\"]. ''Pep.ph''. Retrieved 2014-05-20.</ref>\n* [[2013 GMMSF Box-Office Entertainment Awards|2013 Winner]], Most Popular TV Program News & Public Affairs<ref>[http://www.pep.ph/photos/3796/44th-guillermo-mendoza-box-office-entertainment-awards \"44th Guillermo Mendoza Box-Office Entertainment Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403190603/http://www.pep.ph/photos/3796/44th-guillermo-mendoza-box-office-entertainment-awards |date=April 3, 2019 }}. ''Pep.ph''. Retrieved 2014-05-19.</ref>\n\n:'''Northwest Samar State University Annual Awards'''\n* 2013 Winner, Best News and Public Affairs Program\n* 2013 Winner, Mike Enriquez: Best News and Public Affairs Male Program Anchor\n* 2013 Winner, Mel Tiangco: Best News and Public Affairs Female Program Anchor\n* 2012 Winner, Best News and Public Affairs Program\n* 2012 Winner, Mike Enriquez: Best News and Public Affairs Male Program Anchor\n\n:'''PMAP Makatao Awards for Media Excellence'''\n* 2012 Winner, Best News Program\n* 2012 Winner, Mel Tiangco: Best TV Female Newscaster\n\n:'''National Academy of Television Arts & Science (Emmy Awards)'''\n* 2013 Winner, Best Documentary\n\n==''24 Oras Weekend''==\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = 24 Oras Weekend\n| image = 24 Oras Weekend title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card since 2019\n| genre = [[Newscast]]\n| company = [[GMA News and Public Affairs]]\n| director = Lirio Dayao\n| presenter = {{plain list|\n* [[Pia Arcangel]]\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]]}}\n| theme_music_composer = Jimmy Antiporda\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| executive_producer = Nielsen Ocampo\n| location = {{plainlist|\n* Studio 2, [[GMA Network Center]], [[Quezon City]], Philippines {{small|(2010\u20132011, 2018\u20132019)}}\n* Studio 5, GMA Network Center, Quezon City, Philippines {{small|(2011\u20132018, since 2019)}}}}\n| runtime = 30-45 minutes\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| picture_format = {{plainlist|\n* [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n* [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])}}\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|2010|2|21}}\n| last_aired = present\n}}\n\nOriginally anchored by [[Pia Arcangel]] and [[Jiggy Manicad]], the weekend edition of ''24 Oras'' premiered on February 21, 2010 on the network's Saturday and Sunday night line up replacing ''[[GMA Weekend Report]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=24 Oras Weekend premieres this Sunday, February 21 |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/5612/24-oras-weekend-premieres-this-sunday-february-21 |accessdate=April 26, 2018 |work=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]] |date=February 20, 2012}}</ref> On April 21, 2018, Manicad left the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2018/04/22/1808377/jiggy-manicad-leaves-media-next-level-public-service |title=Jiggy Manicad leaves media for \u2018next level\u2019 of public service {{!}} Philstar.com |website=philstar.com |accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, [[Ivan Mayrina]] became an anchor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/43076/ivan-mayrina-co-anchors-24-oras-weekend/story |title=Ivan Mayrina co-anchors '24 Oras Weekend' |website=www.gmanetwork.com |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Arcangel and Mayrina currently serve as anchors.\n\n===Anchors===\n* [[Pia Arcangel]] {{small|(since 2010)}}\n* [[Ivan Mayrina]] {{small|(since 2018)}}\n* Nelson Canlas {{small|(since 2013, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n\n;Former anchors\n* [[Jiggy Manicad]] {{small|(2010\u20132018)}}\n* [[Grace Lee]] {{small|(2010\u20132012, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n* [[Luane Dy]] {{small|(2010\u20132013, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n* Cata Tibayan {{small|(2013\u20132018, ''Chika Minute'')}}\n\n===Ratings===\nAccording to [[AGB Nielsen Philippines]]' Mega Manila household television ratings, the premiere of ''24 Oras Weekend'' earned a 18.4% rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/news/local/24798/agb-mega-manila-tv-ratings-feb-19-22-panday-kids-and-pilipinas-got-talent-make-strong-impact-on-thei |title=AGB Mega Manila TV Ratings (Feb. 19-22): Panday Kids and Pilipinas Got Talent make strong impact on their debut |author=Santiago, Erwin |date=February 23, 2010 |accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Regional versions==\n*  ''24 Oras Amianan''\n* ''[[24 Oras Bikol]]''\n* ''24 Oras Central Visayas''\n* ''24 Oras Davao''\n* ''[[24 Oras Ilokano]]''\n* ''24 Oras North Central Luzon''\n* ''[[24 Oras Northern Mindanao]]''\n* ''24 Oras Southern Mindanao''\n* ''24 Oras Western Visayas''\n* ''[[Ratsada 24 Oras]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/shows/24oras}}\n* {{IMDb title|0764672}}\n\n{{24 Oras}}\n{{PhilNetworkEveningNewsShows}}\n{{PhilNetworkHourlyNewsBulletins}}\n{{GMA Network (current and upcoming original programming)}}\n{{GMA News and Public Affairs}}\n\n[[Category:GMA Network news programs]]\n[[Category:GMA News and Public Affairs programs]]\n[[Category:Philippine television news programs]]\n[[Category:2004 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s Philippine television series]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Flagship evening news programs]]\n", "name_user": "Hotwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccolades:fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/24_Oras"}
{"title_page": "Allatoona High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox School\n | name                    = Allatoona High School\n | logo                    = Allatoona High School Buccaneer.jpg\n | type                    = [[Public high school]]\n | established             = 2008\n | grades                  = 9\u201312\n | enrollment              = 1731 (2018-19)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1301290&ID=130129003781 Alatoona High School]</ref>\n | teaching_staff          = 88.50 ([[Full time equivalent|FTE]]) <ref name=NCES></ref>\n | ratio                   = 19.56 <ref name=NCES></ref>\n | campus                  = [[Suburb]]an\n | principal               = Candace Wilkes\n | team_name               = Buccaneers\n | rival                   = Harrison Hoyas\n | colors                  = Red and black {{Color box|red|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|black|border=darkgray}}\n | district                = [[Cobb County School District]]\n | accreditation           = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n | streetaddress           = 3300 Dallas Acworth Highway NW\n | city                    = [[Acworth, Georgia|Acworth]]\n | state                   = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n | zipcode                 = 30101\n | country                 = [[United States]]\n | coordinates             = {{coord| 34.035242|-84.735336|display=title,inline|format=dms}}\n | website                 = {{URL|www.cobbk12.org/schools/Allatoona}}\n | footnotes               = <ref name=\"ed.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&Zip=30132&Miles=10&SchoolType=1&SchoolType=2&SchoolType=3&SchoolType=4&SpecificSchlTypes=all&IncGrade=-1&LoGrade=-1&HiGrade=-1&SchoolPageNum=2&ID=130129003781|title=Search for Public Schools - School Detail for Allatoona High School|work=ed.gov|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Allatoona High School''' is one of seventeen  [[state school|public schools]] in the [[Cobb County School District]]. The institution opened in the fall of 2008, and is currently the most recent high school in the district. It is located in suburban [[Acworth, Georgia]], north of Atlanta, in the United States. The school is named after the nearby [[Lake Allatoona]].\n\n==Demographics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1301290&ID=130129003781|title=Search for Public Schools - School Detail for Allatoona High School|website=nces.ed.gov|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>==\nThe demographic breakdown of the 1,731 students enrolled for the 2018\u20132019 school year was:\n*Male - 50.9%\n*Female - 49.1%\n*Native American/Alaskan - 0.1%\n*Asian/Pacific islander - 3.5%\n*Black - 19.4%\n*Hispanic - 10.1%\n*White - 63.3%\n*Multiracial - 3.6%\nIn addition, 17.5% of the students qualified for free or reduced lunches.<ref name=\"ed.gov\"/>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.cobbk12.org/schools/Allatoona/}}\n\n[[File:Allatoona High School, Cobb County, Georgia.JPG|thumb|right|Allatoona High School]]\n\n{{GHSA Class AAAAAA Region 6}}\n{{GeorgiaUS-school-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Cobb County, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox School\n| name = Allatoona High School\n| logo = Allatoona High School Buccaneer.jpg\n| type = [[Public high school]] \n| established = 2008\n| grades = 9\u201312\n| enrollment = 2,212 (2019-20)<ref name=NCES>[https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1301290&ID=130129003781 Alatoona High School]</ref>\n| teaching_staff = 88.30 ([[Full time equivalent|FTE]]) <ref name=NCES></ref>\n| ratio = 19.64 <ref name=NCES></ref>\n| campus = [[Suburb]]an\n| principal = Candace Wilkes\n| team_name = Buccaneers\n| rival = Harrison Hoyas \n| colors = Red and black {{Color box|red|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|black|border=darkgray}}\n| district = [[Cobb County School District]]\n| accreditation = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n| streetaddress = 3300 Dallas Acworth Highway NW\n| city = [[Acworth, Georgia|Acworth]]\n| state = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| zipcode =30101\n| country = [[United States]]\n| coordinates = {{coord| 34.035242|-84.735336|display=title,inline|format=dms}}\n| website = {{URL|www.cobbk12.org/schools/Allatoona}}\n| footnotes = <ref name=\"ed.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&Zip=30132&Miles=10&SchoolType=1&SchoolType=2&SchoolType=3&SchoolType=4&SpecificSchlTypes=all&IncGrade=-1&LoGrade=-1&HiGrade=-1&SchoolPageNum=2&ID=130129003781|title=Search for Public Schools - School Detail for Allatoona High School|work=ed.gov|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Allatoona High School''' is one of seventeen  [[state school|public schools]] in the [[Cobb County School District]]. The institution opened in the fall of 2008, and is currently the most recent high school in the district. It is located in suburban [[Acworth, Georgia]], north of Atlanta, in the United States. The school is named after the nearby [[Lake Allatoona]].\n\n==Demographics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1301290&ID=130129003781|title=Search for Public Schools - School Detail for Allatoona High School|website=nces.ed.gov|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>==\nThe demographic breakdown of the 1,731 students enrolled for the 2018\u20132019 school year was:\n*Male - 50.9%\n*Female - 49.1%\n*Native American/Alaskan - 0.1%\n*Asian/Pacific islander - 3.5%\n*Black - 19.4%\n*Hispanic - 10.1%\n*White - 63.3%\n*Multiracial - 3.6%\nIn addition, 17.5% of the students qualified for free or reduced lunches.<ref name=\"ed.gov\"/>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.cobbk12.org/schools/Allatoona/}}\n\n[[File:Allatoona High School, Cobb County, Georgia.JPG|thumb|right|Allatoona High School]]\n\n{{GHSA Class AAAAAA Region 6}}\n{{GeorgiaUS-school-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Cobb County, Georgia]]\n", "name_user": "F1reant", "label": "safe", "comment": "update on enrollment numbers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allatoona_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Homeschooling international status and statistics", "text_new": "{{Circular|hgygnjv. Bbhgggguuioate=February 2019|date=March 2020}}\n[[Homeschooling]] is legal in many countries. Countries with the most prevalent home education movements include [[Australia]], Canada, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, and the United States. Some countries have highly regulated home education programs as an extension of the compulsory school system; others, such as [[Germany]],<ref name=Spiegler>{{cite journal|last=Spiegler |first=Thomas |title=Home education in Germany: An overview of the contemporary situation |url=http://www.multilingual-matters.net/erie/017/0179/erie0170179.pdf |journal=Evaluation and Research in Education |year=2003 |volume=17 |pages=179\u201390|format=PDF |doi=10.1080/09500790308668301}}</ref> have outlawed it entirely. In other countries, qpr are the best while not restricted by law, homeschooling is not socially acceptable, or considered undesirable and is virtually non-existent.\n\n[[File:Legality_of_Homeschooling_2019_Sept.svg|thumb|alt=Map of homeschool laws worldwide|400px|\n'''Legal status of homeschooling across the world'''\n----\n{{legend|#2aff80ff|Homeschooling is legal}}\n{{legend|#ffd42aff|Homeschooling is legal with certain restrictions}}\n{{legend|#ff2a2aff|Homeschooling is illegal}}\n{{legend|#E0E0E0|Legal status unknown/unclear}}\n]]\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Status of homeschooling across continents ==\n\n=== Africa ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! style=\"width:130px\" | Country or Region\n! style=\"width:760px\" | Status\n! style=\"width:175px\" | Statistics\n! style=\"width:100px\" | Sources\n|-\n| Sierra Leone\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| \n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://planipolis.iiep.unesco.org/upload/Sierra%20Leone/SL_Act03_Education.pdf |format=PDF |title=Supplement to the Sierra Leone Gazette Vol. CXXXV, No. 19 |date=1 April 2004 |quotation=THE EDUCATION ACT, 2004 |website=Planipolis.iiep.unesco.org |accessdate=2016-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082322/http://planipolis.iiep.unesco.org/upload/Sierra%20Leone/SL_Act03_Education.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|South Africa\n| Legal as alternative to the mandatory public school system.\n| Estimated between 30 000 and 100 000 children\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sahomeschoolers.org/|title=SA Homeschoolers - Blog Articles|author=|date=|website=www.sahomeschoolers.org}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== North America ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! style=\"width:130px\" | Country or Region\n! style=\"width:760px\" | Status\n! style=\"width:175px\" | Statistics\n! style=\"width:100px\" | Sources\n|-\n| Canada\n| Legal under regulating conditions (Alberta \u2013 regulation, British Columbia \u2013 registration, Manitoba \u2013 permit, Newfoundland \u2013 permit, New Brunswick \u2013 permit, Northwest Territories \u2013 regulation, Nova Scotia \u2013 regulation, Ontario \u2013 regulation, Prince Edward Island \u2013 regulation, Quebec \u2013 permit, Saskatchewan \u2013 permit, Yukon \u2013 regulation)\n| 60,000+\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ontariohomeschool.org/about-homeschooling/homeschooling-faq/|title=The Ontario Federation of Teaching Parents \u00bb Homeschooling FAQ|author=|date=|website=ontariohomeschool.org}}</ref><ref>http://www.hslda.org/docs/nche/000000/00000080.asp</ref><ref>http://www.hslda.org/docs/news/2012/201203271.asp</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canadianliving.com/life-and-relationships/subsection/family|title=Family|author=|date=|website=Canadian Living}}</ref>\n|-\n| Greenland\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://fleksibelskole.dk/atuarfitsialak_en.htm|title=Atuarfitsialak Engelsk|author=|date=|website=fleksibelskole.dk}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Greenland \u2013 MSN Encarta |url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761561107/greenland.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028015907/http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761561107/Greenland.html |archivedate=2009-10-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| United States\n| Legal under regulating conditions, varies by state.\n| Around 2.5 million\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://hslda.org/content/laws/|title=Homeschool Laws in Your State - HSLDA|first=Home School Legal Defense|last=Association|date=|website=Home School Legal Defense Association}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Latin America and the Caribbean ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! style=\"width:130px\" | Country or Region\n! style=\"width:760px\" | Status\n! style=\"width:175px\" | Statistics\n! style=\"width:100px\" | Sources\n|-\n| Belize\n| Expats have right to homeschool. Compulsory attendance is unclear for citizens.\n| Unknown\n|\n|-\n| Brazil\n| Unknown. The federal supreme court has never made a pronouncement on homeschooling, leaving its legalization unknown. But in 2019, with a new project, Homeschooling can be legalized in the country.<ref>http://portal.mec.gov.br/component/content/article?id=75061</ref>\n| 7000 families\n| <ref>[[Constitution of Brazil]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.camara.leg.br/camaranoticias/radio/materias/COM-A-PALAVRA/444758-DEPUTADO-DIZ-QUE-E-IMPORTANTE-AVALIACAO-PERIODICA-DE-CRIANCAS-QUE-SAO-EDUCADAS-DENTRO-DE-CASA.html|title=Deputado diz que \u00e9 importante avalia\u00e7\u00e3o peri\u00f3dica de crian\u00e7as que s\u00e3o educadas dentro de casa|author=|date=|website=www2.camara.leg.br}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/noticias/2013/11/131104_educacao_domiciliar_abre_vale_mdb|title=Ensinar os filhos em casa ganha for\u00e7a no Brasil e gera pol\u00eamica|first=Mariana Della Barba Da BBC Brasil em S\u00e3o|last=Paulo|date=|website=BBC News Brasil}}</ref>\n|-\n| Chile\n| Legal. Freedom of education is guaranteed by the constitution.  Prior registration with the Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n is required.\n| 8000 - 15000 students\n| <ref>https://www.ayudamineduc.cl/ficha/examenes-libres-menores-de-18-anos-11</ref>\n|-\n| Colombia\n| Legal. Regulated by the Ministry of Education and the [[ICFES]] (Colombian Institute for the Promotion of Higher Education). The student would have to present a Public Validation Test and a State Test (Similar to SAT) if he/she wants to go to College.\n| N/A\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.icfes.gov.co/|title=Novedades - Icfes Instituto Colombiano para la Evaluaci\u00f3n de la Educaci\u00f3n|author=|date=|website=www2.icfes.gov.co}}</ref>\n|-\n| Costa Rica\n| Illegal, public or private education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| \n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://homeschoolingcostarica.org|title=\u00bfEs legal el homeschooling en Costa Rica? No|author=|date=|website=homeschoolingcostarica.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hslda.org/content/hs/international/CostaRica/default.asp|title=HSLDA - Home Schooling - Costa Rica|author=|date=|website=hslda.org}}</ref>\n|-\n| Cuba\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n| [[Education in Cuba|WP]]{{Circular reference|date=February 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Cuba|title=Cuba - history - geography|author=|date=|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/Americas/Cuba-EDUCATION.html|title=Education - Cuba|author=|date=|website=www.nationsencyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| El Salvador\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n|\n|-\n| Guatemala\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Unknown\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Guatemala|title=Guatemala - History, Map, Flag, Population, & Facts|author=|date=|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/Americas/Guatemala-EDUCATION.html|title=Education - Guatemala|author=|date=|website=www.nationsencyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| Mexico\n| Legal as long as the student is registered, which can be a lengthy bureaucratic process. Compulsory attendance laws are unclear.\n| Unknown\n|\n|-\n| Panama\n| Unclear, for it is neither legal nor illegal.\n|\n|\n|-\n| Peru\n| Legal. Prior registration with the Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n is required.\n|\n|\n|-\n| Suriname\n| Legal.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dna.sr/wetgeving/surinaamse-wetten/geldende-teksten-tm-2005/de-lager-onderwijswet-1960|title=De Lager Onderwijswet 1960 - De Nationale Assembl\u00e9e|author=|date=|website=www.dna.sr}}</ref>\n|-\n| Trinidad and Tobago\n| Legal.\n| Unknown\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://hslda.org/content/hs/international/trinidadtobago/default.asp|title=HSLDA - Home Schooling - Trinidad & Tobago|author=|date=|website=hslda.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.homeschool-life.com/1450/faq/?public=1&private=|title=FAQs|author=|date=|website=www.homeschool-life.com}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Asia ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! style=\"width:130px\" | Country or Region\n! style=\"width:760px\" | Status\n! style=\"width:175px\" | Statistics\n! style=\"width:100px\" | Sources\n|-\n| Armenia\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n| [[Education in Armenia|WP]]{{Circular reference|date=February 2019}}<ref>http://www.bibl.u-szeged.hu/oseas/armedu.html</ref>\n|-\n| Azerbaijan\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n| [[Education in Azerbaijan|WP]]{{Circular reference|date=February 2019}}<ref name=\"countrystudies.us\">{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/azerbaijan/23.htm|title=Azerbaijan - Education, Health, and Welfare|author=|date=|website=countrystudies.us}}</ref>\n|-\n| Georgia\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n| <