\n|2016\n|Best Supporting Actor\n|[[Mikkel Boe F\u00f8lsgaard]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Best Production Design\n|Gitte Malling \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Best Costume Design\n|Stefanie Bieker \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Best Make-Up\n|Barbara Kreuzer \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Best Sound\n|Rasmus Winther Jensen \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Best Original Score\n|Sune Martin\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n|rowspan=2|[[Rotterdam International Film Festival]]\n|Warsteiner Audience Award\n|Land of Mine\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite web|author1=International Film Festival Rotterdam|title=Moviezone Award|url=https://iffr.com/en/about-iffr/awards/iffr-audience-award|website=iffr.com|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=International Film Festival Rotterdam|title=Warsteiner Audience Award|url=https://iffr.com/en/about-iffr/awards/iffr-audience-award|website=iffr.com|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|MovieZone Award\n|Land of Mine\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2016\n|rowspan=2|[[Sydney Film Festival]]\n|Audience Award\n|Land of Mine\n|{{draw|2nd Place}}\n|rowspan=2|\n|-\n|2016\n|Sydney Film Prize\n|Land of Mine\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[89th Academy Awards|2017]]\n|[[Academy Awards]]\n|[[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n|Land of Mine\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"Oscars2017\">{{cite news |url=http://edit.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/oscar-nominations-2017-complete-list-nominees-960044 |title=Oscars: 'La La Land' Ties Record With 14 Nominations |first=Kimberly |last=Nordyke |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=24 January 2017 |accessdate=24 January 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"OscarsVar\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/2017-oscar-nominations-academy-awards-nominees-1201968107/ |title=Oscar Nominations: Complete List |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=24 January 2017 |accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Australian Film Critics Association]]\n| Best International Film (Foreign Language)\n| ''Land of Mine''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=The 2018 AFCA Awards|url=http://www.afca.org.au/afca-2018-film--writing-awards.html|publisher=[[Australian Film Critics Association]]|accessdate=28 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314095057/http://www.afca.org.au/afca-2018-film--writing-awards.html|archivedate=14 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 89th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Danish submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* ''[[Ten Seconds to Hell]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3841424|Land of Mine}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|land_of_mine}}\n\n{{Martin Zandvliet}}\n{{Bodil Award for Best Danish Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Land Of Mine}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s war drama films]]\n[[Category:Danish films]]\n[[Category:Danish drama films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:German war drama films]]\n[[Category:Danish-language films]]\n[[Category:German-language films]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoner of war films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1945]]\n[[Category:Danish war films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2015 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Land of Mine\n| image          = Land of Mine.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| film name      = ''Under sandet''\n| director       = [[Martin Zandvliet]]\n| producer       = Malte Grunert<br>Mikael Chr. Rieks\n| screenplay     = Martin Zandvliet\n| starring       = [[Roland M\u00f8ller]]<br>[[Mikkel F\u00f8lsgaard]]\n| music          = Sune Martin\n| cinematography = Camilla Hjelm Knudsen\n| editing        = Per Sandholt<br>Molly Malene Stensgaard\n| distributor    = [[Nordisk Film]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|9|10|[[2015 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2015|12|3|Denmark|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = Denmark<br>Germany\n| language       = German<br>Danish\n| budget         = 35.5 million [[Danish krone|DKK]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Nordisk Film & TV Fond Jumps On Zandvliet\u2019s Land of Mine|url=http://www.nordiskfilmogtvfond.com/index.php/news/stories/nordisk-film-tv-fond-jumps-zandvliets-land-mine/|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $3.1 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=landofmine.htm|title=Under sandet (Land of Mine) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Land of Mine''''' ({{lang-da|'''Under sandet'''|lit=Under the Sand}}) is a 2015 Danish-German [[historical drama|historical]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[war film]] directed by [[Martin Zandvliet]]. It was shown in the Platform section of the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/toronto-international-film-festival-announces-inaugural-platform-lineup-including-world-premiere-of-ben-wheatleys-high-rise-20150813 |title=Toronto International Film Festival Announces Inaugural Platform Lineup |accessdate=14 August 2015 |work=IndieWire}}</ref> It was selected and nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] category at the [[89th Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"Denmark\">{{cite web|url=http://cphpost.dk/news/war-film-submitted-as-denmarks-oscar-entry.html |title=War film submitted as Denmark\u2019s Oscar entry |work=CPH Post |date=19 September 2016 |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"HWR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-denmarks-land-mine-picked-930779 |title=Oscars: Denmark Selects 'Land of Mine' for Foreign-Language Category |first=Scott |last=Roxborough |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=19 September 2016 |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Oscar\">{{cite news|last1=Samuelson|first1=Kate|title=Here Are the 2017 Oscar Nominations|url=http://time.com/4635815/2017-oscars-nominations-list/|accessdate=24 January 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film is inspired by real events and tells the story of [[Germany|German]] [[prisoners of war]] sent to clear [[land mines]] in [[Denmark]] after [[Denmark in World War II|World War II]]. It is estimated that over two thousand German soldiers, including numerous teenagers, under the command of German officers but against the [[Geneva Conventions]], removed mines, nearly half of them being either killed or wounded. The removal was part of a controversial agreement between the German Commander General [[Georg Lindemann]], the Danish Government and the British Armed Forces, under which German soldiers with experience in defusing mines would be in charge of clearing the mine fields. Historians have criticised the film for showing German soldiers clearing mines under the command of Danish officers, which never happened.<ref>{{cite web|title=UNDER SANDET - NY FILM AF MARTIN ZANDVLIET|url=http://www.dfi.dk/Nyheder/FILMupdate/2014/Juni/Under-sandet-ny-film-af-Martin-Zandvliet.aspx#|accessdate=9 November 2015|language=Danish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://politiken.dk/kultur/art5601303/Historiker-roser-Under-Sandet-selv-om-der-skrues-%C2%BBliiige-lovligt-meget-p%C3%A5-drama-knappen%C2%AB|title=Historiker roser 'Under Sandet' selv om der skrues \u00bbliiige lovligt meget p\u00e5 drama-knappen\u00ab|first=Eva Lange J\u00f8rgensen|last=Journalist|date=3 December 2015|website=Politiken|accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nFollowing the [[end of World War II in Europe]] and the [[liberation of Denmark]] from [[German occupation of Denmark|German occupation]] in May 1945, the defeated ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' evacuates the country. A Danish sergeant, Carl Leopold Rasmussen, furiously beats up a German [[prisoner of war]] for carrying a [[Flag of Denmark|Danish flag]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/danish-postwar-drama-land-of-mine-tells-a-little-known-story/article34048206/|title=Danish postwar drama Land of Mine tells a little known story|last=|first=|date=|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=13 June 2018}}</ref> A group of young German prisoners are handed over to the [[Royal Danish Army|Danish Army]] and sent to the [[Atlantic Wall|west coast]], where they are trained to [[Demining|remove the mines]] that the Germans had buried in the sand. Rasmussen forces the boys to perform the dangerous work with their bare hands. They are warned not to expect any sympathy from the Danes, who resent their former occupiers. Rasmussen shares this contempt and he is determined to treat the young prisoners without sympathy.\n\nRasmussen is rude to and contemptuous of them and the neighbouring household treats them with hostility. After marching his squad onto the dunes, he promises that they will return home in three months, if they can each defuse six mines per hour for a total of 45,000 mines. Rasmussen begins to grow conflicted in his feelings and Sebastian Schumann, leader of the boys, attempts to remain optimistic; the boys discuss their plans for when they return home.\n\nThe POWs are not given food due to postwar shortages and some begin to suffer from [[malnourishment]]. The optimistic Wilhelm's arms are blown off and he dies in a [[field hospital]]. After stealing animal fodder from the nearby farm, the boys are poisoned by rat droppings and Rasmussen forces them to purge themselves with seawater. Afterwards, he begins to treat them more kindly, stealing food from the base for them and reporting that Wilhelm has survived, to maintain morale. He also allows the boys to use a device invented by Sebastian to improve productivity. While clearing the beach, one of the boys forgets to separate a mine's plunger from the detonator.  After Rasmussen stops a group of Allied soldiers from urinating on one of the boys, Ebbe accuses him of being sympathetic towards the Germans. Werner is blown to bits after encountering landmines buried one above another and his twin brother, Ernst, who is in [[denial]], is comforted by Rasmussen.\n\nAfter a casual game of [[soccer|football]], Rasmussen's dog is blown up in a supposedly safe zone of the beach.  This causes Rasmussen to snap and begin abusing the boys again. He forces them to march close together across the cleared zones of the beach to confirm that they are safe. He relents after seeing Ernst save a little girl from the minefield and then commit suicide by walking onto uncleared sand.  He reassures a grieving Sebastian that they will soon be able to return. While four of the boys continue to clear the beach of mines, a live mine is accidentally tossed onto a truckload of deactivated mines, setting off a massive chain reaction and killing the other seven. Only Sebastian, Ludwig, Helmut and Rodolf remain.\n\nAlthough the boys had been promised that they would be sent home after defusing all of the mines, Ebbe informs Rasmussen that he has ordered the surviving four to be sent to another area, to join a team defusing landmines without the aid of a map. Rasmussen argues with Ebbe but he refuses to rescind the order. Rasmussen rescues them, drives them within 500 meters of the [[Denmark\u2013Germany border|German border]] and orders them to run to their freedom.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Roland M\u00f8ller]] as Sgt. Carl Leopold Rasmussen \n* [[Mikkel Boe F\u00f8lsgaard]] as Captain Ebbe Jensen\n* Laura Bro as Karin\n* [[Louis Hofmann]] as Sebastian Schumann\n* [[Joel Basman]] as Helmut Morbach\n* Oskar B\u00f6kelmann as Ludwig Haffke\n* Emil Belton as Ernst Lessner\n* Oskar Belton as Werner Lessner\n* [[Leon Seidel]] as Wilhelm LeBern\n* Karl Alexander Seider as Manfred\n* Maximilian Beck as August Kluger\n* August Carter as Rodolf Selke\n* Tim B\u00fclow as Hermann Marklein\n* Alexander Rasch as Friedrich Schnurr\n* Julius Kochinke as Johann Wolff\n* Zoe Zandvliet as Elizabeth\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nFilming began in July 2014 and ended in August 2014. The film was shot at historically authentic locations, including in [[Oksb\u00f8l Refugee Camp|Oksb\u00f8llejren]] and areas in [[Varde]]. The use of the historical beaches led to the [[unexploded ordnance|discovery of a real live mine]] during the production.<ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|author1=AFI|authorlink1=American Film Institute|title=Award Winners - Land of Mine|url=http://afifest.afi.com/2016/sections/t5527|website=AFI Fest|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n''Land of Mine'' received critical acclaim. Film review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a 91% \"Certified Fresh\" rating, with an average score of 7.4/10, based on reviews from 99 critics. The website's critical consensus states: \"''Land of Mine'' uses an oft-forgotten chapter from the aftermath of World War II to tell a hard-hitting story whose period setting belies its timeless observations about bloodshed and forgiveness.\"<ref>{{Rotten Tomatoes|land_of_mine}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 75 out of 100, based on 26 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{metacritic film|land-of-mine}}</ref>\n\nThe film gained a standing ovation at the [[Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Monggaard|first1=Christian|title=Giant Canadian Hug|url=http://www.information.dk/545063|accessdate=11 December 2015|language=Danish}}</ref> with Stephen Farber of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' stating \"Director Martin Zandvliet has come up with a fresh and compelling approach to this well-traveled territory\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Farber|first1=Stephen|title='Land of Mine': TIFF Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/land-mine-tiff-review-820282|publisher=The Hollywood Review|accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref> and David D'Arcy of the ''Screendaily'' stating \"''Land of Mine'' achieves moments of chilling suspense in scenes of untrained soldiers defusing mines by hand and in the bloody bodies that leap into the air when the boys fail\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Arcy|first1=David|title='Land Of Mine': Review|url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/land-of-mine-review/5092868.article|website=ScreenDaily|accessdate=11 December 2015|language=Danish}}</ref> Domestically it received 5 out of 6 stars from a number of critics, who all stated it was the best Danish film of the year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Land of Mine|url=http://www.ekkofilm.dk/anmeldelser/under-sandet/|accessdate=11 December 2015|language=Danish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Olsen|first1=Jesper|title=Review|url=http://soundvenue.com/film/2015/12/under-sandet-174023|accessdate=11 December 2015|language=Danish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Carlsen|first1=Per Juul|title=A Kick in the Head for National Feeling|url=http://www.dr.dk/nyheder/kultur/film/anmeldelse-et-spark-i-skridtet-paa-den-danske-nationalfoelelse|accessdate=11 December 2015|language=Danish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kastrup|first1=Kim|title=Land of Mine is Number 1|url=http://ekstrabladet.dk/filmmagasinet/Filmnyheder/under-sandet-ligger-nummer-1/5863594|accessdate=11 December 2015|language=Danish}}</ref> It was selected to play at [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=SUNDANCE INSTITUTE COMPLETES FEATURE FILM LINEUP FOR 2016 SUNDANCE FILM FESTIVAL|url=http://www.sundance.org/blogs/news/premieres-spotlight-sundance-kids-and-special-events-announced-for-2016-festival|website=Sundance|accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=LAND OF MINE HEADING TO SUNDANCE|url=http://www.cinemascandinavia.com/land-of-mine-sundance/|accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Land of Mine'' has also won numerous awards, including [[Bodil Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]], [[Bodil Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actor]] and [[Bodil Award for Best Danish Film|Best Danish Film]] at the [[Bodil Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=/ritzau/|title=Bodil Party: Post war drama wins big|url=http://www.b.dk/kultur/bodil-fest-efterkrigsdrama-vinder-store-danske-priser|website=b.dk|publisher=Berlinske|accessdate=7 March 2016|language=Danish}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n! Ref(s)\n|-\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Gij\u00f3n International Film Festival]]\n|Audience Award\n|Land of Mine\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Hamburg Film Festival]]\n|Art Cinema Award\n|Land of Mine\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|rowspan=2|[[Tokyo International Film Festival]]\n|Tokyo Grand Prix\n|Land of Mine\n|{{nom}}\n|rowspan=2|\n|-\n|2015\n|Best Actor Award\n|Roland M\u00f8ller & Louis Hofmann \n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[2015 Toronto International Film Festival|2015]]\n|[[Toronto International Film Festival]]\n|Platform Prize\n|Land of Mine\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|[[AFI Fest]]\n|World Cinema Audience Award\n|Land of Mine\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\"AFI\" />\n|-\n|2016\n|rowspan=3|[[Bodil Awards]]\n|[[Bodil Award for Best Danish Film|Best Danish Film]]\n|Land of Mine\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=3|<ref>{{cite web|title=Bodil Awards 2016|url=http://www.bodilprisen.dk/aar-for-aar/2016-2/|website=Bodilprisen.dk|accessdate=5 February 2017|language=Danish}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Bodil Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]]\n|Roland M\u00f8ller\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Bodil Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actor]]\n|[[Louis Hofmann]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[29th European Film Awards|2016]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[European Film Awards]]\n|[[European Film Award for Best Cinematographer|Best Cinematographer]]\n|Camilla Hjelm Knudsen\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"| <ref name=\"EFA\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/global/malgorzata-szumowskas-body-wins-peoples-choice